    id: 'Y8N01',
    title: 'The James Webb Space Telescope: Humanity\'s Deepest Eye',
    type: 'nonfiction',
    source: 'Original (factually grounded)',
    text: 'On Christmas Day 2021, a rocket carrying the most powerful space telescope ever built lifted off from the Guiana Space Centre in South America. The James Webb Space Telescope — known as JWST — had taken over thirty years and approximately ten billion dollars to design and construct. For astronomers around the world, the launch was the culmination of careers spent in anticipation. For the rest of humanity, it was the beginning of a new era in our understanding of the universe.\n\nThe telescope is named after James E. Webb, the NASA administrator who oversaw the Apollo programme during the 1960s. Unlike its predecessor, the Hubble Space Telescope, which orbits relatively close to Earth at around 600 kilometres above the surface, JWST operates nearly 1.5 million kilometres away — a location known as the second Lagrange point, or L2. At this distance, the telescope remains in a stable position aligned with the Earth and the Sun, allowing it to observe deep space without interference from our planet\'s heat or light.\n\nWhat makes JWST truly revolutionary is its ability to detect infrared light — a wavelength invisible to the human eye. Because the universe is expanding, light from the most distant galaxies is stretched into the infrared spectrum as it travels towards us, a phenomenon called redshift. By capturing this light, JWST can peer back in time over 13 billion years, revealing galaxies that formed shortly after the Big Bang. Hubble could observe the universe to a depth of around 400 million years after the Big Bang; Webb reaches back to within 100 million years of that event.\n\nThe telescope\'s primary mirror is composed of eighteen hexagonal gold-plated segments, spanning 6.5 metres in diameter — too large to fit inside any rocket in its unfolded state. Engineers designed it to fold origami-style for launch and unfold automatically in space. This deployment process, which NASA engineers described as \'six months of terror\' compressed into two weeks, involved over three hundred individual mechanisms, each of which had to function perfectly. A single failure would have rendered the entire instrument useless.\n\nThe first full-colour images released by NASA in July 2022 were breathtaking. A photograph known as Webb\'s First Deep Field showed thousands of galaxies — some appearing as faint smudges of light — in a patch of sky no larger than a grain of sand held at arm\'s length. Other images revealed stellar nurseries, dying stars, and the atmospheric composition of an exoplanet 1,150 light-years from Earth. Scientists detected carbon dioxide in the atmosphere of the exoplanet WASP-39b — the first time this molecule had been identified in a planet outside our solar system.\n\nJWST is expected to operate for at least twenty years, though it carries enough fuel for potentially much longer. Its discoveries are already rewriting textbooks and challenging existing models of how galaxies form and evolve. In the words of NASA administrator Bill Nelson, Webb is \'a new window into the history of our universe.\' Whether it will find evidence of conditions that could support life elsewhere remains one of science\'s most tantalising open questions.',
