        skill: 'Evaluation',
        marks: 8,
        guidance: 'Indicative content: critical evaluation of the writer\'s methods and the extent to which the text is one-sided or balanced. Reward a clear, supported viewpoint with textual references. Award marks for: identifying the celebratory, awe-inspiring tone throughout; recognising moments that acknowledge difficulty/risk ("six months of terror", "a single failure would have rendered the entire instrument useless"); noting use of authoritative voices (NASA administrator Bill Nelson) which may be seen as partial; evaluating whether the writer\'s enthusiasm undermines or enhances credibility; considering whether the omission of criticism (cost controversy, delays) makes the text promotional. L8: perceptive, evaluative, well-evidenced; L6: clear, supported judgement; L4: some evaluation with evidence; L2: simple comment with limited support.',
        model: 'Model answer: There is considerable truth in the reader\'s view: the passage is predominantly celebratory in tone, marshalling an impressive range of facts and superlatives to present JWST in an overwhelmingly positive light. The writer uses language such as "breathtaking" and "revolutionary," and the closing quotation from NASA\'s own administrator — "a new window into the history of our universe" — means the article ends on a promotional note from someone with a direct interest in the telescope\'s success. The article makes no mention of the project\'s lengthy delays, the political controversies over its cost, or any scientific limitations, which a genuinely balanced piece of journalism might be expected to address.\n\nHowever, I only partly agree with the reader, because the writer does acknowledge risk and the possibility of catastrophic failure. The description of the deployment as requiring "over three hundred individual mechanisms, each of which had to function perfectly," followed by the blunt statement that "a single failure would have rendered the entire instrument useless," introduces real tension and acknowledges the precariousness of the enterprise. This is not the language of uncritical promotion — it shows the reader that success was far from guaranteed. Furthermore, the use of precise data (specific distances, dates, temperatures) throughout the article lends scientific credibility and suggests the writer is informing rather than merely celebrating. Overall, while the tone is undeniably enthusiastic, the passage contains enough acknowledgement of complexity and risk to qualify as informative science writing rather than pure advertisement.'
