        guidance: 'Indicative content: identify methods AND comment on effect with quotation. Methods to reward: emotive language ("grief", "dismantling", "stranger to us"); precise statistics used to shock ("3.41 million square kilometres", "280 billion tonnes"); contrast between beauty and destruction (opening description of aurora/glaciers against "fastest-warming"); direct quotation from Inuit elder to humanise and authenticate; listing of affected regions (Bangladesh to Miami) to show global scale; verb choices ("heed", "dismantling"); rhetorical open question at the end. L4 perceptive; L3 clear; L2 some comment; L1 simple.',
        model: 'Model answer: The writer opens with lyrical, positive language — "extraordinary, desolate beauty," "aurora borealis" — which makes the subsequent revelation that Svalbard is "one of the fastest-warming places on Earth" all the more shocking through contrast. This structural use of juxtaposition makes the threat feel visceral rather than abstract. The writer also uses precise statistics throughout, such as "280 billion tonnes per year" and "3.41 million square kilometres," which lend scientific authority and make the scale of the problem impossible to dismiss. Perhaps most powerfully, the Inuit elder\'s quotation — \'The weather has become a stranger to us\' — uses simple, human language to communicate profound loss, giving an emotional weight that statistics alone cannot achieve. The closing rhetorical question, "whether humanity will heed it in time," places responsibility directly on the reader, making the article feel urgent and personally relevant.'
