        guidance: 'Indicative content: evaluate the writer\'s portrayal of Shackleton and whether it is admirably thorough or uncritically celebratory. Reward: identifying the overwhelmingly positive presentation; acknowledging the explicit mention of the expedition\'s failure as an achievement ("not the triumph he had envisioned, but something arguably greater"); considering the phrase "whatever one thinks of the era in which Shackleton lived" as a gesture towards complication; evaluating whether the omission of Shackleton\'s personal flaws (financial failures, complicated marriages, drinking) limits the portrait; discussing the use of Amundsen\'s quotation; evaluating whether the passage\'s purpose (biography, not exposé) justifies a focused, admiring portrait. L8: perceptive, balanced, well-evidenced; L6: clear and supported; L4: some evaluation; L2: basic.',
        model: 'Model answer: The reader\'s characterisation of the passage as hagiography is partially justified: the portrait of Shackleton is overwhelmingly admiring, and the writer makes no mention of significant aspects of his life that would complicate the picture — his repeated financial difficulties, the strain his expeditions placed on his family, or the fact that the Trans-Antarctic expedition was itself a failure in terms of its stated objective. A genuinely rounded biography would engage with these contradictions. The accumulation of superlatives — "most remarkable," "greatest feat" — and the final tribute from Amundsen do give the passage a celebratory quality that sits closer to eulogy than balanced assessment.\n\nHowever, I think the charge of hagiography is too strong. The writer acknowledges from the outset that the expedition was not "the triumph he had envisioned," framing success as a form of salvage rather than accomplishment — a nuanced point that avoids simple triumphalism. The closing qualifier, "whatever one thinks of the era in which Shackleton lived," is a deliberate acknowledgement that his story cannot be separated from its historical context, including the imperialism and social hierarchies of Edwardian exploration, even if the writer does not pursue this strand. This suggests an awareness of complexity rather than naive hero-worship. Ultimately, the passage is a biographical profile with an admiring but coherent argument: that Shackleton\'s leadership methods have enduring value. Judged by that purpose, the portrait is convincing and well-evidenced, even if a longer treatment would benefit from greater balance.'
