        model: 'Model answer: The writer uses a powerful simile to introduce Jaisalmer — "rises from the Thar Desert like a hallucination" — which immediately conveys the city\'s dreamlike quality and prepares the reader for an experience that transcends the ordinary. The choice of "hallucination" suggests something almost unreal, catching the reader\'s imagination before they can become complacent. In the description of the market, the writer appeals to multiple senses simultaneously: the fabrics are not merely colourful but so vivid "they seemed to vibrate," turning colour into a physical sensation. The accumulation of colour terms — "amber, gold, rust, deep copper" — when describing the dunes at sunset creates a painterly effect, slowing the prose to encourage the reader to linger visually on the scene. The writer also uses the direct address "No photograph prepares you for it," which creates a sense of intimacy and draws the reader into the narrator\'s experience of genuine surprise, making the description feel spontaneous rather than rehearsed.'
