    text: 'Inside your digestive system, right now, there are approximately 38 trillion microorganisms — bacteria, viruses, fungi, and other microscopic life — that together weigh roughly the same as your brain. This community of organisms, known as the gut microbiome, has until recently been treated by medicine as a background detail, a biological footnote. Over the past two decades, however, the science of the microbiome has transformed our understanding of human health in ways that are still unfolding. Far from being merely passengers in our bodies, the microorganisms in our gut may be active participants in everything from our immune function to our mental health.\n\nThe relationship between humans and their gut bacteria is one of the oldest partnerships in biology. We provide bacteria with a warm, nutrient-rich environment; they, in return, perform tasks our own cells cannot. Gut bacteria break down dietary fibres that the human digestive system cannot process, producing short-chain fatty acids that nourish the cells lining the gut wall. They synthesise certain vitamins, including vitamin K and some B vitamins. They train the immune system — roughly 70 per cent of our immune cells are located in the gut — to distinguish between harmful pathogens and harmless substances. A healthy, diverse microbiome is, in this sense, not a luxury but a biological necessity.\n\nWhat constitutes a healthy microbiome is still an active area of research, but scientists have identified several consistent patterns. Greater diversity of bacterial species is generally associated with better health outcomes. Studies have found that people in industrialised countries tend to have less diverse microbiomes than people in rural, non-industrialised communities, a difference attributed partly to diet — specifically, lower fibre intake and greater consumption of processed foods — and partly to widespread antibiotic use. Antibiotics are essential medicines, but their effect on the microbiome is indiscriminate: they kill harmful bacteria and helpful ones alike. A course of antibiotics can reduce gut microbial diversity significantly, and while the microbiome typically recovers, recovery is not always complete.\n\nOne of the most striking recent developments is research linking the gut microbiome to brain health and mood — a connection described as the gut-brain axis. The gut produces approximately 90 per cent of the body\'s serotonin, a neurotransmitter associated with mood regulation, and contains over 100 million nerve cells — more than the spinal cord. Studies in mice have shown that transferring gut bacteria from anxious mice into germ-free mice causes the recipients to exhibit anxiety-like behaviours. In humans, research has found associations between certain microbiome profiles and conditions including depression, anxiety, and autism spectrum disorder — although the nature of these relationships (whether altered microbiomes cause these conditions, or result from them) remains under investigation.\n\nFor most people, the most practical implication of microbiome science is relatively straightforward: eat more plants. A diet rich in diverse plant foods — vegetables, fruits, legumes, whole grains, nuts and seeds — provides the dietary fibre that beneficial gut bacteria use as fuel. A landmark study published in the journal Cell in 2021 found that a high-fibre diet and a diet rich in fermented foods (yoghurt, kefir, kimchi, sauerkraut) both increased microbiome diversity and reduced markers of inflammation in healthy adults. These are not exotic interventions; they are, broadly speaking, the dietary patterns that traditional food cultures around the world have followed for millennia.\n\nThe gut microbiome is not a magic key to perfect health, and the science is far from complete. Commercially available probiotic supplements have shown inconsistent results in clinical trials, and the microbiome-influencing claims of many food products are not well supported by evidence. But the broader principle — that the health of the human body depends on a complex web of relationships between our own cells and the organisms that live within us — represents a genuine and important shift in how medicine understands what it means to be healthy.',
