        model: 'Model answer: The writer immediately engages the reader with the second-person address, "Inside your digestive system, right now," which is direct and intimate, making an abstract scientific topic feel personally relevant before a single fact has been stated. The statistic that follows — "approximately 38 trillion microorganisms" — is designed to astonish, and its impact is reinforced by the comparison "weigh roughly the same as your brain," which translates an incomprehensible number into a familiar physical image. This technique of anchoring abstract data to concrete, familiar reference points continues throughout the passage. The phrase "Far from being merely passengers in our bodies" uses a metaphor that most readers will immediately visualise, and the correction it introduces — that microorganisms are "active participants" — creates a moment of reframing that makes the reader feel they are learning something genuinely surprising. The writer also uses the language of relationship and reciprocity — "one of the oldest partnerships in biology," "we provide... they, in return" — which presents complex biology as a kind of social arrangement, making it emotionally as well as intellectually accessible.'
